@NODE Intro "Super-Select - Introduction."

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Introduction@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}Super-Select is a program which will pick a random string, insert
it between two other strings, and (optionally) execute the result as if it
were typed in a shell window.
@{par}
@{par}Can't think of how that could be useful?
@{par}
@{par}Well, say you want a random picture displayed whenever you boot your
Amiga. The "random string" could be chosen from a file conatining a list of
the files in your pictures drawer, and the turned into a command line which
displayed that picture!
@{par}
@{par}Or, you could make it copy one of the files in the list somewhere so
that it appeared as your Workbench backdrop-picture...
@{par}
@{par}You could even use it as a fortune cookie program, making the "say"
command speak a randomly selected phrase...
@{par}
@{par}It is even possible to have a random command executed!
@{par}
@{par}I hope that you can think of some cool use for this program to make
your Amiga a bit different everytime you boot...
@{par}
@{par}During my boot-up (which is quite long given the amount of things
I run on my 68000 A500) I have one of my 293 boot-pictures shown by @{b}Visage@{ub},
while the theme music from either @{i}Babylon 5 @{ui}(series 2), @{i}Mission Impossible@{ui},
or @{i}Lost In Space @{ui}plays. When the boot is finished I also play a random
sample from my collection of 276 (including 107 @{i}Beavis'n'Butthead @{ui}samples).
@{par}
@{par}@{b}What makes it better than other similar utils?@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}I have see one or two programs which do similar things to
Super-Select, but instead of taking the random string from a file, they
scan a directory and randomly choose a file within it. This means that they
waste ages when you have more than a few files in the directory.
@{par}
@{par}Super-Select takes the filename (or whatever) from a list which
means it can do the selection very quickly, and also means that you
are not limited to randomly selecting filenames.
@{par}
@{par}
@{par}Also, with version 2 of Super-Select there is an
@{" Exclude mode " LINK U_Exclude_Mode} which ensures that no line in the list is used twice
before every line has been selected, so you can be sure that every one of
your files will be shown to you, even if my random number routine is less
than perfect.
@{par}
@{par}I hope you like it!

@ENDNODE
@NODE Requirements "Super-Select - Requirements"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Requirement@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}You don't need anything fancy to run Super-Select, just AmigaOS 2 or
above and the desire to do something with it. :-)

@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation "Super-Select - Installation"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Installation@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}Just copy the executable to wherever it is you keep this type of
program and the Amigaguide to wherever it is you keep the docs for this
type of program. Then get writting those scripts!

@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage "Super-Select - Usage."

@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Usage@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par} @{" Help      " LINK U_Help}  Brings up this help text.
@{par}
@{par} @{" ListFile  " LINK U_ListFile}  Path to the Super-Select list file.
@{par} @{" Before    " LINK U_Before}  String which goes before the random string.
@{par} @{" After     " LINK U_After}  String which goes after the random string.
@{par}
@{par} @{" Delay     " LINK U_Delay}  Number of seconds to wait after command.
@{par} @{" NoExclude " LINK U_NoExclude}  Disable @{" Exclude mode " LINK U_Exclude_Mode}.
@{par} @{" NoSpaces  " LINK U_NoSpaces}  Don't insert spaces around random string.
@{par} @{" Report    " LINK U_Report}  Output the resultant command-line for checking.
@{par} @{" NoExec    " LINK U_NoExec}  Don't execute the command-line (use with Report).
@{par} @{" NoReq     " LINK U_NoReq}  Disable error requesters.
@{par}
@{par} @{" InText    " LINK U_InText}  Text file for conversion to list format.
@{par} @{" OutList   " LINK U_InText}  Path to write converted list to.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}Notes:@{uu}@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{" Exclude Mode " LINK U_Exclude_Mode}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{" Notes on the list files " LINK U_ListFileNotes}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} To include spaces in a string, @{fg shine}"surround it with quotes"@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} To include quotes in your string, use *" instead of "
@{par}  For example:  @{fg shine}"He said *"HELLO*"!"@{fg text}  =  @{fg shine}He said "HELLO"!@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}ReadArgs() Template:@{uu}@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}HELP/S, L=LISTFILE/K, B=BEFORE/K, A=AFTER/K, D=DELAY/K/N, NOEXCLUDE/S,
NOSPACES/S, REPORT/S, NOEXEC/S, NOREQ/S, INTEXT/K, OUTLIST/K

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Help "Super-Select - Usage, Help"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Help@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}Help@{fg text} is a @{b}switch@{ub} which will dump the help-text to the shell window when
given.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_ListFile "Super-Select - Usage, ListFile"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}ListFile@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}The ListFile @{b}keyword@{ub} is used to tell Super-Select where the list file
(created with the @{" InText and OutList" LINK U_InText} commands) you wish the line to
be randomly selected from is.
@{par}

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Before "Super-Select - Usage, Before"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Before@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}The Before @{b}keyword@{ub} takes a string which is placed before the randomly
chosen string when the command-line is built.
@{par}
@{par}You do not have to have a Before string - leaving it out will mean that
the randomly chosen string is first in the command-line and the program
will run a randomly chosen command!

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_After "Super-Select - Usage, After"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}After@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}The After @{b}keyword@{ub} takes a string which is placed after the randomly
chosen string when the command line is built.
@{par}
@{par}You do not have to have an After string.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Delay "Super-Select - Usage, Delay"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Delay@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}The Delay @{b}keyword@{ub} takes a @{b}number@{ub} and causes Super-Select to pause for
that number of seconds after executing the command-line. This allows
you to @{i}run @{ui}a program and let it set itself up before letting the
script (user-startup or whatever) continue. This should speed things
up as there is less disk thrashing.
@{par}
@{par}If you specify @{fg shine}Delay=0@{fg text} or don't even use the Delay keyword, no delay
will take place.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NoSpaces "Super-Select - Usage, NoSpaces"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}NoSpaces@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}Normally, a space is inserted before and after the randomly chosen string
because most of the time this string will be a filename which must be
separated from everything else on the command-line.
@{par}
@{par}If you specify the NoSpaces @{b}switch@{ub}, these spaces will not be added.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Report "Super-Select - Usage, Report"

@{par}See also: @{" NoExec " LINK U_NoExec}
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Report@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}If you specify the Report @{b}switch@{ub}, the resultant command-line which is
generated by the program will be output to the Shell window so that you
can check that everthing is working OK.
@{par}
@{par}You can also use redirection with the Report switch when running
Super-Select in a script to send all commands to a log file which you
can inspect should something not work. (Say you have a corrupted
picture which leaves you with no bootpic when you reset. Normally you
wouldn't have a clue which file was just chosen but with this you can
just look in the log).
@{par}
@{par}Remember that you can use @{fg shine}>>@{fg text} instead of @{fg shine}>@{fg text} when redirecting a program's
output so that it will APPEND rather than overwrite whatever used to be
there.
@{par}
@{par}e.g: @{bg fill} Super-Select >>S:SS_Log.TXT B "TEST" L "S:List" Report @{bg back}

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NoExec "Super-Select - Usage, NoExec"

@{par}See also: @{" Report " LINK U_Report}
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}NoExec@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}If you specify the NoExec @{b}switch@{ub} the program will generate a command-line
as normal, but not execute it.
@{par}
@{par}Used in conjunction with the @{" Report " LINK U_Report} switch, NoExec makes it easy for you
to make sure the program is generating the right command-lines without it
actually executing them and wasting a lot of time.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NoReq "Super-Select - Usage, NoReq"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}NoReq@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}By default, all error messages are displayed in a requester. For most
people this should be ideal as if something goes wrong in the
startup-sequence (which is usually run so that you don't see the output
of anything) you'll get a nice requester telling you what went
wrong.
@{par}
@{par}However, if your Amiga is running in some kind of automated environment
like a BBS where you don't want a reboot or script of any kind to be
halted by an error (or if the error requesters simply bug you), you can
use the NoReq @{b}switch@{ub} to disable the requesters and redirect all error
messages to the shell window.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NoExclude "Super-Select - Usage, NoExclude"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}NoExclude@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}The NoExclude @{b}switch@{ub} disables @{" Exclude mode " LINK U_Exclude_Mode}.
@{par}
@{par}When the NoExclude switch is given one of the lines in the listfile is
chosen at random regardless of whether it has already been selected or not,
and it is not marked as selected.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Exclude_Mode "Super-Select - Usages, Exclude Mode"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Exclude Mode@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}Exclude mode is the default behaviour of Super-Select and can be disabled
by the @{" NoExclude " LINK U_NoExclude} switch.
@{par}
@{par}In Exclude mode, when a line is randomly selected from a list file it is
marked as selected and will not be chosen again until every other line
in the file has been used as well.
@{par}
@{par}Exclude mode is great because it stops some pictures (samples, quotes,
etc.) being used much more often than others and ensures that no
picture is just wasting space on your harddrive.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_ListFileNotes "Super-Select - Usage, List file notes"

@{par}@{uu}@{fg shine}Notes on the List Files@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}Note that the list file must be on non-writeprotected media as even with
the @{" NoExclude " LINK U_NoExclude} switch Super-Select still needs to save a new random
number seed to the list file after each selection. If this is a problem
for anyone I can easily add the option not to do this (maybe someone wants
to put out a CD which has a 'lucky-dip' script on it or something).
@{par}
@{par}Another thing which you should note is that if you make two copies of a
listfile and run Super-Select on both of them, the same line will be
selected because they will both contain the same random number seed.
(New seeds are generated when you create the list and when every line of
the list has been selected).

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_InText "Super-Select - Usage, InText and OutList"

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}InText and OutList@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}The list files which Super-Select uses to choose a line from are not
normall ASCII files: they also contain data about which lines have been
selected (for @{" Exclude mode " LINK U_Exclude_Mode}) as well as a random number seed and some
other things.
@{par}
@{par}To create a Super-Select list file you must have an ASCII file containing
a bunch of lines (every line, including the last must end with a return).
You are currently limited to 32,767 lines, which should be enough for
all but the die-hard picture collector.
@{par}
@{par}See the @{" Examples " LINK Examples} section for easy ways of generating the ASCII file.
@{par}
@{par}To get Super-Select to convert your ASCII file, give its path to the
@{fg shine}InText@{fg text} @{b}keyword@{ub} and specify where to output the resultant Super-Select
list using the @{fg shine}OutList@{fg text} @{b}keyword@{ub}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Examples "Super-Select: Examples."

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}Examples@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}Typing:
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}@{bg fill} Super-Select ListFile S:PicsList Before DH0:Art/Visage Delay 2 @{bg back}
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}...where S:PicsList is a list file converted from the following:
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par} DH2:Pictures/Sex/Pervert/Cindy_Crawford.IFF
@{par} DH2:Pictures/Sex/Pervert/NakedPowerPCBoard.IFF
@{par} DH2:Pictures/Sex/Pervert/Sheep.IFF
@{par} DH2:Pictures/Sex/Pervert/Amiga4000_060.IFF
@{par} DH2:Pictures/Sex/Pervert/Your_Mum.IFF
@{par} DH2:Pictures/Really_Hot_Stuff/SGI_Workstation.IFF
@{par} DH2:Pictures/Really_Hot_Stuff/Ethernet_Connection.IFF
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}...would run a command-line such as:
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}@{bg fill} DH0:Art/Visage DH2:Pictures/Sex/Pervert/Amiga4000_060.IFF @{bg back}
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}...and then wait 2 seconds.
@{par}
@{par}
@{par}Typing:
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}@{bg fill} Super-Select L S:PicsList B "Copy >NIL: FROM" A "TO DH0:WBBackdrop.PIC" @{bg back}
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}...would run a command-line such as:
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}@{bg fill} Copy >NIL: FROM DH2:Pictures/Sex/Pervert/Sheep.IFF TO DH0:WBBackdrop.PIC @{bg back}
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}
@{par}To create the @{i}S:PicsList @{ui}used in this example, let's say you want to include all
pictures in @{i}DH2:Pictures/ @{ui}and its subdirectories in your list.
@{par}
@{par}First, you can generate the ASCII list using the @{i}AmigaDOS List @{ui}command:
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}@{bg fill} List >T:PicList_TMP DH2:Pictures/ LFormat="%f%s" All Files @{bg back}
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}(Of course, you could create the file by hand in a text editor).
@{par}
@{par}If you also had a directory called @{i}DH2:Pictures/Too_Dirty_To_Show/ @{ui}which
you didn't want displayed you can use the Amiga's powerful pattern
matching: (All one one line, of course)
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}@{bg fill} List >T:PicList_TMP DH2:Pictures/(Sex|Really_Hot_Stuff)/ LFormat="%f%s"
@{par}@{bg fill} All Files @{bg back}
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}(If you want to know more about AmigaDOS pattern matching read an AmigaDOS
manual or the Autodocs, don't expect me to explain it <grin>).
@{par}
@{par}Once you've got the ASCII file, converting it is simple:
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}@{bg fill} Super-Select InText T:PicList_TMP OutList S:PicsList @{bg back}
@{par}---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{par}
@{par}I hope you've got the idea.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "CheckGuide" "CheckGuide by Eddy Carroll"

@{par}          @{fg shine}CheckGuide 1.0 -- Checks AmigaGuide files for common errors
@{par}
@{par}             by Eddy Carroll, September 1994. Freely distributable.@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}Introduction
@{par}
@{par}If you've ever tried creating even a modestly sized AmigaGuide file by hand,
@{par}you'll have discovered that it can be quite difficult to keep track of all the
@{par}various links and cross references. As your help file gets larger, it gets
@{par}increasingly harder to ensure that you have remembered to reference all the
@{par}nodes in the file from at least one place, and haven't left any unresolved
@{par}links.
@{par}
@{par}CheckGuide is a simple utility that can detect several common errors in
@{par}AmigaGuide files. The errors it can detect are:
@{par}
@{par}· Extra plain text between an \@ENDNODE and \@NODE (AmigaGuide won't allow such
@{par}  text to ever be displayed)
@{par}
@{par}· Nodes that are defined but not referenced from any other node. Unless your
@{par}  program directly instructs AmigaGuide to access such nodes, the user won't
@{par}  easily be able to access them.
@{par}
@{par}· Links to help nodes that aren't defined within the file.
@{par}
@{par}· Open braces with no preceding \@ character (usually a simple typo).
@{par}
@{par}· \@{" Button "} constructs with no LINK command (an easy mistake to make if
@{par}  you're entering a lot of them).
@{par}
@{par}All of these options can be selectively enabled or disabled.
@{par}
@{par}        @{fg shine}CheckGuide was used in the creation of @{b}THIS@{ub} document!@{fg text}

@ENDNODE
@NODE AGIX "AGIX by Ralph Seichter"

@{par}          @{fg shine}@{u}From: AGIX.doc 1.2 (5.8.94) Copyright © Ralph Seichter@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg text}PURPOSE:
@{par}
@{par}   Although  AmigaGuide documents may have a node index, only few documents
@{par}make  use of this feature. I suppose that many people are too lazy to build
@{par}an  index  manually (I definitely am), so I thought it would be a good idea
@{par}to have this task done automatically. AGIX scans an AmigaGuide document for
@{par}references  like  \@{"foo" link "bar"} (note that AGIX does not use the node
@{par}definitions), sorts them alphabetically and produces an index file.
@{par}
@{par}   "Haven't I seen something like that before?" you might ask. Well, I have
@{par}seen  one  similar  program  so far, but on my machine it didn't work, so I
@{par}decided  to  try  it myself. The result is short (only 1960 bytes) and uses
@{par}StrnCmp() from locale.library instead of stricmp(), if available, and has a
@{par}very nice sounding name. :)

@ENDNODE
@NODE History "Super-Select - History."

@{par}@{u}@{fg shine}History@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Version numbering is in the @{fg shine}<version>@{fg fill}.@{fg shine}<revision>@{fg text} format. This means
@{par}      that version @{fg shine}1.10 @{fg text}(one.ten) is @{b}newer@{ub} than version @{fg shine}1.2 @{fg text}(one.two).
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.0 - 4-Jan-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}First@{ub} release.
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v2.2 (Released to Aminet) - 25-Mar-1996 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Major@{ub} recode, please read the guide.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Most important addition is the new @{" Exclude mode " LINK U_Exclude_Mode}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} No longer works on ASCII file lists. Don't worry, @{" conversion " LINK U_InText} is easy!

@Remark VERSION NUMBERS/DATES: VER string and Contents Node.
@Remark WHEN ADDING NEW NODES, DON'T FORGET TO UPDATE THE INDEX.

@ENDNODE
